1. Git-native first.
2. Bash + git only.
3. Self-documenting CLI.
4. Docs, code, tests, and skill stay in sync.
5. Test with real agents.
6. Branch for features.
7. Agent-native by default.
8. Dogfood the tool while building it.
9. Prefer jj workspaces over git worktrees for parallel local work. This repo hit confusing states when a temporary git worktree carried the active checkout while the canonical local path looked like the repo but behaved like the git dir. jj workspaces fit the intended workflow better and are easier to reason about.
